The Flint Adolescent Study (FAS) is a longitudinal interview study of risk and promotive factors associated with alcohol, tobacco and other drug use across a lifetime.
The study is led by Marc A. Zimmerman, Ph.D., Director of the Prevention Research Center and the Michigan Youth Violence Prevention Center at the University of Michigan School of Public Health. Hsing-Fang Hsieh, PhD, Research Investigator at the UM School of Public Health is the Project Director. Data is collected by the Michigan Public Health Institute.
The Flint Adolescent Study and Flint Adolescent Study-Generation 2 are funded by the National Institute on Drug Abuse.
